  "query": "What are the documented effects of adding soil amendments like charcoal, sulphur, or carbon before or after seeding on grassland vegetation?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on documented studies, charcoal amendments to grassland soil before seeding showed mixed effects: one Netherlands study found no change in overall plant biomass or grass cover, but increased legume cover while not affecting other forbs (Action 3422). Sulphur amendments demonstrated varied impacts: two studies (UK and USA) showed sulphur added before seeding either reduced plant species richness or had no effect, reduced overall vegetation cover in one UK study, but increased cover of some sown species at low application rates (Action 3428). Sulphur added alongside seeding showed no consistent increase in heather cover in UK studies, though one study found increased heather seedling survival initially (Action 1710). Carbon amendments applied after seeding in two USA studies either reduced or had no effect on density of sown forb species (Action 3433). Overall, these amendments showed inconsistent effects on grassland vegetation, with outcomes varying by amendment type, application timing, and target species.",
